1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,000
 You already know the basic loop, embed your docs,

2
00:00:04,000 --> 00:00:07,200
 embed the query, grab the nearest chunks.

3
00:00:07,200 --> 00:00:10,080
 We will skip that because what actually decides

4
00:00:10,080 --> 00:00:14,300
 whether retrieval works happens earlier at indexing time

5
00:00:14,300 --> 00:00:16,840
 and most setups get it wrong.

6
00:00:16,840 --> 00:00:18,340
 Start with chunking.

7
00:00:18,340 --> 00:00:20,440
 The moment you split a document up,

8
00:00:20,440 --> 00:00:23,420
 each chunk loses the context around it.

9
00:00:23,420 --> 00:00:28,340
 A line like the fee is $50 gets stored as a naked blob

10
00:00:28,340 --> 00:00:32,300
 with no record that it lived under Section 4 refunds.

11
00:00:32,300 --> 00:00:34,720
 Retrieve it later and the model has no idea

12
00:00:34,720 --> 00:00:36,300
 what it's looking at.

13
00:00:36,300 --> 00:00:38,840
 Chunks too big and you drag in noise.

14
00:00:38,840 --> 00:00:40,980
 Too small and you lose the meaning.

15
00:00:40,980 --> 00:00:42,920
 This one decision sets a ceiling

16
00:00:42,920 --> 00:00:45,360
 on how good your system can get.

17
00:00:45,360 --> 00:00:47,560
 There's a useful upgrade here.

18
00:00:47,560 --> 00:00:50,540
 Anthropic calls it contextual retrieval.

19
00:00:50,540 --> 00:00:54,280
 Before you embed a chunk, a cheap model writes a short note

20
00:00:54,280 --> 00:00:58,020
 on where it sits in the document and prepends it.

21
00:00:58,020 --> 00:01:01,600
 So the fee is $50 becomes in the refund policy,

22
00:01:01,600 --> 00:01:03,320
 the fee is $50.

23
00:01:03,320 --> 00:01:06,640
 Same chunk, but now it carries its context.

24
00:01:06,640 --> 00:01:09,520
 In an anthropic own testing, that single change

25
00:01:09,520 --> 00:01:13,440
 to the embedding's cut field retrievals by about a third

26
00:01:13,440 --> 00:01:16,720
 before you have even touched the search.

27
00:01:16,720 --> 00:01:20,240
 Fix the index and everything downstream gets easier.

